	<h3 id="theme1">About Kawwa2 and the Kawwa Portal</h3>

	<div class="k-panel">
		<h4 class="control"><a href="#" title="Click to fold/unfold block">What is the "Kawwa Portal"?</a></h4>
		<div class="content k-article">
			<p>The Kawwa Portal is a new interface for Kawwa, the Kit for Atos Worldline Applications, based on the "component approach", 
			which means you may assemble your web pages with just what you need, helping to reduce the time of interface development.</p>
			<p>This new interface was created to improve the way Kawwa guidelines are applied and to extend those guidelines to other kinds 
			of web sites, and not only to web applications. In this sense, you will be able to find in the portal components like articles, product sheets, etc.</p>
			<p class="k-readmore">For more information about the portal or about Kawwa components, please refer to the "<a >All About Kawwa</a>" pages.</p>
		</div>
	</div>

	<div class="k-panel">
		<h4 class="control"><a href="#" title="Click to fold/unfold block">What do you call "Kawwa Components"?</a></h4>
		<div class="content k-article">
			<p>In the Kawwa Portal, a component is an element of a web page that is made of a specific HTML code, specific CSS declarations and, 
			in the case of rich components, the javascript code used to apply it to the page and, eventually, a set of javascript files.</p>
			<p>What makes them "components" is the fact that <strong>they're "independent" of the context where they will be applied</strong>. In other words, a 
			component can be applied to an existing site, with an existing HTML code and style-sheet, and it can "fit" in the existing site easily.</p>
			<p>For example, a sliding pannel block (a block that folds/unfolds its content like this one) is a component made of some lines of HTML code 
			(to structure the component and to give it the classes or ids needed), its predefined CSS declarations and the javascript instructions 
			necessary to apply it to the page in order to be interactive (to fold/unfold itself).</p>
			<p><strong>Note that the CSS declarations are always optional</strong>. You may add the component's declarations to your existing style-sheet, 
			or you may simply let your component inherit styles already defined in your site.</p>
			<p class="k-readmore">For more information about the portal or about Kawwa components, please refer to the "<a >All About Kawwa</a>" pages.</p>
		</div>
	</div>

	<div class="k-panel">
		<h4 class="control"><a href="#" title="Click to fold/unfold block">My web application was developped over Kawwa1.6. Can I upgrade it with the new Kawwa components?</a></h4>
		<div class="content k-article">
			<p>As this new version of Kawwa implied a major change not just in the way you will work with it, but also in the chosen approach, the code used on Kawwa 1.6 templates 
			was reviewed and it is today relatively different (there were major class names changes). In that way, there will be no direct upgrade from version 1.6 to version 2.</p>
			<p>Note that if your application follows the best practices and guidelines of Kawwa 1.6 templates, it presents the same quality as Kawwa2, 
			and there will be no problem to make it richer by adding to it the new rich Kawwa components as you would do with any other web application.</p>
			<p><strong>If your application is developed over Tapestry and uses Tapestry Kawwa Components</strong>, the upgrade in this case will be transparent, as those components will be modified 
			directly in Tapestry.</p>
			<p class="k-readmore">For more information about the portal or about Kawwa components, please refer to the "<a >All About Kawwa</a>" pages.</p>
		</div>
	</div>

